  <section class="weis-section">
    <div class="weis-section-label">
      <span class="weis-section-label-num">04</span>
      <span class="weis-section-label-text">Decision Log</span>
      <span class="weis-section-label-line"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="weis-decision-list">

      <div class="weis-decision-card">
        <div class="weis-decision-header">
          <span class="weis-decision-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-title">MVC 5 + Web API 2 Over Modern SPA</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-problem">The project needed both server-rendered views for complex reporting dashboards and REST endpoints for real-time data. In 2018, .NET Core was still in 2.x and lacked full SignalR support. The engineering team was already proficient in full .NET Framework.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-chosen"> Chosen — MVC 5 + Web API 2</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-text">Dual pipeline approach: MVC controllers delivered server-rendered Kendo UI views with Knockout.js MVVM binding for interactivity. Web API 2 provided 20+ REST endpoints consumed by the frontend for dynamic data. Shared service layer prevented logic duplication.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — .NET Core / SPA</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-text">.NET Core 2.1 was emerging but SignalR support was experimental. Migrating to a React/Angular SPA would have doubled delivery time and required retraining the existing ASP.NET team. Infrastructure was Windows-only at project start.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-code">
<pre><span class="weis-token-cm">// Dual pipeline — MVC controller + Web API in same project</span>
[<span class="weis-token-fn">Authorize</span>]
<span class="weis-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">WellActivityController</span> : Controller
&#123;
    <span class="weis-token-kw">public</span> ActionResult <span class="weis-token-fn">Index</span>()
    &#123;
        <span class="weis-token-kw">return</span> View(<span class="weis-token-fn">_service</span>.<span class="weis-token-fn">GetDashboardData</span>());
    &#125;
&#125;

[<span class="weis-token-fn">RoutePrefix</span>(<span class="weis-token-str">"api/wells"</span>)]
<span class="weis-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">WellApiController</span> : ApiController
&#123;
    [<span class="weis-token-fn">Route</span>(<span class="weis-token-str">"&#123;id&#125;/cost"</span>)]
    <span class="weis-token-kw">public</span> IHttpActionResult <span class="weis-token-fn">GetCostBreakdown</span>(<span class="weis-token-kw">string</span> id)
    &#123;
        <span class="weis-token-kw">var</span> result = <span class="weis-token-fn">_costService</span>.<span class="weis-token-fn">GetWaterfall</span>(id);
        <span class="weis-token-kw">return</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">Ok</span>(result);
    &#125;
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="weis-decision-card">
        <div class="weis-decision-header">
          <span class="weis-decision-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-title">MongoDB + Oracle Dual-Database Strategy</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-problem">Well exploration data has two distinct profiles: rapidly changing operational data (activity logs, cost waterfalls, real-time comms) and stable master/reference data (well structures, organizational hierarchies, historical records). A single RDBMS struggled with the schema flexibility needed for operational data.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-chosen"> Chosen — MongoDB + Oracle</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-text">MongoDB handled operational data with flexible schemas — well activities, cost breakdowns, and real-time messages. Oracle (via EF 6) managed master data with strict referential integrity — organizational units, well master records, and user authentication. A service layer abstracted the dual source transparently.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — Single RDBMS / NoSQL</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-text">Pure Oracle would have required complex EAV patterns for flexible operational data. Pure MongoDB would lose ACID guarantees for master reference data that needed strict relationships. Dual database added operational complexity but matched each data domain's natural characteristics.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-code">
<pre><span class="weis-token-cm">// Service layer abstracts dual-database access</span>
<span class="weis-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">WellService</span> : IWellService
&#123;
    <span class="weis-token-kw">private readonly</span> MongoCollection&lt;WellActivity&gt; _ops;
    <span class="weis-token-kw">private readonly</span> IWellMasterRepository _master;

    <span class="weis-token-kw">public</span> WellActivityDto <span class="weis-token-fn">GetWellData</span>(<span class="weis-token-kw">string</span> wellId)
    &#123;
        <span class="weis-token-kw">var</span> master = <span class="weis-token-fn">_master</span>.<span class="weis-token-fn">GetById</span>(wellId);  <span class="weis-token-cm">// Oracle</span>
        <span class="weis-token-kw">var</span> activity = <span class="weis-token-fn">_ops</span>.<span class="weis-token-fn">FindById</span>(wellId); <span class="weis-token-cm">// MongoDB</span>
        <span class="weis-token-kw">return new</span> WellActivityDto &#123; Well = master, Activity = activity &#125;;
    &#125;
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="weis-decision-card">
        <div class="weis-decision-header">
          <span class="weis-decision-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-title">Knockout.js + Kendo UI Instead of React</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-problem">The reporting dashboards needed complex data grids, pivot tables, charts, and Excel-like interactions. Building these UI components from scratch or with a pure React ecosystem would have been prohibitively time-consuming for an engineering-focused team.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-chosen"> Chosen — Kendo UI + Knockout.js MVVM</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-text">Kendo UI provided production-ready grids, charts, and scheduling widgets out of the box — critical for waterfall cost charts and rig scheduling. Knockout.js MVVM pattern bound Kendo widgets to ViewModels cleanly. Reduced UI development by ~60% compared to building custom components.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — React Ecosystem</div>
            <div class="decision-text">React with AG-Grid or similar would have offered better long-term maintainability and a larger community. However, the learning curve for the existing team, plus the need for extensive custom widget building, outweighed the benefits given the project's aggressive timeline.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-code">
<pre><span class="weis-token-cm">// Knockout ViewModel binding to Kendo UI grid</span>
<span class="weis-token-kw">function</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">WaterfallViewModel</span>() &#123;
    <span class="weis-token-kw">var</span> self = <span class="weis-token-kw">this</span>;
    self.wells = ko.<span class="weis-token-fn">observableArray</span>([]);
    self.selectedWell = ko.<span class="weis-token-fn">observable</span>();

    self.<span class="weis-token-fn">loadCostWaterfall</span> = <span class="weis-token-kw">function</span>() &#123;
        $.<span class="weis-token-fn">getJSON</span>(<span class="weis-token-str">"/api/wells/"</span> + self.<span class="weis-token-fn">selectedWell</span>() + <span class="weis-token-str">"/cost"</span>)
            .<span class="weis-token-fn">done</span>(<span class="weis-token-kw">function</span>(data) &#123;
                $(<span class="weis-token-str">"#waterfallGrid"</span>).<span class="weis-token-fn">data</span>(<span class="weis-token-str">"kendoGrid"</span>)
                    .<span class="weis-token-fn">dataSource</span>.<span class="weis-token-fn">data</span>(data);
            &#125;);
    &#125;;
&#125;
ko.<span class="weis-token-fn">applyBindings</span>(<span class="weis-token-kw">new</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">WaterfallViewModel</span>());</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="weis-decision-card">
        <div class="weis-decision-header">
          <span class="weis-decision-num">04</span>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-title">SignalR for Real-Time Communications</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-problem">Engineering teams needed instant notifications when cost estimates changed, when well activities were updated, and for urgent messages. Polling-based approaches would have created unacceptable latency and database load.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-chosen"> Chosen — SignalR 2.4 WebSocket</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-text">SignalR established persistent WebSocket connections between the browser and the OWIN-hosted hub. When any well activity or cost estimate changed, the server pushed updates to all connected clients in real-time. Automatic fallback to long-polling when WebSocket was unavailable. Integrated with OWIN middleware seamlessly.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-label weis-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — gRPC / Server-Sent Events</div>
            <div class="weis-decision-col-text">gRPC streaming would have required proto definitions and .NET Core. SSE only supported one-way server-to-client communication without native .NET library support in 2018. SignalR was the mature, well-supported choice for the .NET Framework ecosystem.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="weis-decision-code">
<pre><span class="weis-token-cm">// SignalR hub broadcasting cost updates to all clients</span>
<span class="weis-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">CostHub</span> : Hub
&#123;
    <span class="weis-token-kw">public async Task</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">NotifyCostChange</span>(<span class="weis-token-kw">string</span> wellId, CostUpdate update)
    &#123;
        <span class="weis-token-kw">await</span> Clients.All.<span class="weis-token-fn">costUpdated</span>(wellId, update);
    &#125;
&#125;

<span class="weis-token-cm">// Startup.cs — OWIN configuration</span>
<span class="weis-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">Startup</span>
&#123;
    <span class="weis-token-kw">public void</span> <span class="weis-token-fn">Configuration</span>(IAppBuilder app)
    &#123;
        app.<span class="weis-token-fn">MapSignalR</span>();
    &#125;
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="weis-section">
    <div class="weis-section-label">
      <span class="weis-section-label-num">05</span>
